	"__INITIAL_DATA__": {"comments":{"id":500,"count":103,"talk_id":610},"threadId":500,"current_talk":"610","description":"Willard Wigan tells the story of how a difficult and lonely childhood drove him to discover his unique ability -- to create art so tiny that it can't be seen with the naked eye. His slideshow of figures, as seen through a microscope, can only be described as mind-boggling.","event":"TEDGlobal 2009","language":"en","name":"Willard Wigan: Hold your breath for micro-sculpture","slug":"willard_wigan_hold_your_breath_for_micro_sculpture","speakers":[{"id":"483","slug":"willard_wigan","is_published":true,"firstname":"Willard","lastname":"Wigan","middleinitial":"","title":"","description":"Micro-sculptor","photo_url":"https://pe.tedcdn.com/images/ted/106877_254x191.jpg","whatotherssay":"It was a fantasy world I escaped to where my dyslexia didn't hold me back and my teachers couldn't criticize me. That's how my career as a micro-sculptor began.","whotheyare":"Willard Wigan sculpts figures small enough to fit on the head of a pin. To create these microscopic masterpieces, he works diligently through the stillest hours of the night, between his own heartbeats.","whylisten":"<p>Willard Wigan has immortalized the Obama family in the eye of a needle and Muhammad Ali on the head of a match. In producing sculptures so incredibly small, he works under a microscope and employs ingenious tools, such as a fly&#39;s hair or an ex-girlfriend&#39;s eyelash for paintbrushes. <br /><br />This passion for the diminutive stems from feelings of insignificance in Wigan&#39;s childhood. He was severely dyslexic but undiagnosed, and his teachers&#39; harsh words drove him to hide in a nearby shed where he made shoes and hats for his friends, the ants. Today, his art has earned him national honors and critical acclaim, proving that some treasures can&#39;t be seen with the naked eye.</p>"}],"url":"https://www.ted.com/talks/willard_wigan_hold_your_breath_for_micro_sculpture","v